<DocsLayout title="About" description="What is sens.legal and who is behind it.">
  <h1>About</h1>

  <h2>What is sens.legal?</h2>

  <p>
    sens.legal is an ecosystem in development for traceable legal infrastructure
    in Brazil. Instead of collapsing everything into a single product, it separates
    responsibilities by source of authority: jurisprudence, legislation, doctrine,
    and user experience.
  </p>

  <p>
    The platform is composed of four projects: <a href="/projects/valter">Valter</a>
    as the central jurisprudence and reasoning backend, <a href="/projects/juca">Juca</a>
    as the frontend hub for lawyers, <a href="/projects/leci">Leci</a> as the
    document-first legislation engine, and <a href="/projects/douto">Douto</a> as
    a local doctrine pipeline and internal artifact supplier.
  </p>

  <h2>Who</h2>

  <p>
    sens.legal is created by <strong>Diego Sens</strong>, a lawyer (OAB/PR 96.036) and
    software engineer building the tools he wished he had as a legal professional.
    The combination of domain expertise and engineering means every design decision
    comes from real practice — not an outside interpretation of the field.
  </p>

  <h2>Vision</h2>

  <p>
    Make legal research, grounding, argumentation, and verification accessible to
    lawyers and LLMs without giving up traceability. Every claim should point to a
    real source; every answer should remain explainable.
  </p>

  <h2>What makes it different</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Four-project ecosystem</strong> — the institutional portal describes
      four complementary pieces, not three: Valter, Juca, Leci, and Douto. Each
      has a clear role and integration contract.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Valter as central backend</strong> — the current direction is to move
      legal backend logic out of Juca and consolidate retrieval, reasoning,
      verification, and API/MCP surfaces in Valter.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Grounding by authority source</strong> — Leci is responsible for what
      statutes say, Douto prepares internal doctrinal artifacts, and Valter organizes
      jurisprudence and reasoning over those inputs.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Canonical integration surfaces</strong> — REST API and MCP live in
      Valter's docs, avoiding stale manual inventories in the portal.
    </li>
  </ul>

